node.title: A question about the reference to the MaterialProperty in Material class
node.bodyText:
For example, a no-const reference _diffusivity of MaterialProperty ie declared in Example 8, and it is initialized by function declareProperty("diffusivity"). However, the parameter in the function is only a string for the name of property. So, does _diffusivity[_qp] have the assignment operations during initialization? Would it also work if we just declare MaterialProperty _diffusivity directly? Continuing to learn MOOSE, and looking forward to a reply.
Thank you!

Hello
Sorry for the delay we missed this.
A Material object declares new material properties. Then this material also provides the definition to compute the vlaue of these properties. Computing and setting the value, done with diffusivity[_qp] =  is not a const-compatible operation, hence the on-const reference held by the object
Guillaume

Thank you!
According to the definition of MaterialProperty class, the object of MaterialProperty class must be referenced to avoid the shallow copy problem. According to my current understanding, this may be the main reason that we don't declare MaterialProperty _diffusivity; directly?

It s more that if you don’t take a reference, then you are making a copy of the property.
If you make a copy of the property in your kernel for example, then when the Material object updates the properties, you don’t see the updated values in the copy
Guillaume

I agree with your explanation, so we use constant reference in the Kernel. But in our own Material class, we declare the member variable MaterialProperty<Real> & _diffusivity; rather than MaterialProperty<Real>  _diffusivity;. After reading the source file of MaterialProperty class, now I think this may be a choice made by MOOSE to facilitate development and avoid the shallow copy problem?

It's not const because you want to write to it. It's a reference because because all material properties are registered and managed in a warehouse, thus the object declaring it only holds a reference. There is no shallow copy problem here.
Got! Thank you Guillaume and hugary1995.

node.title: How to Incorporate Thermo-Mechanical Coupling into Fluid-Solid Conjugate Heat Transfer
node.bodyText:
Hi, moose experts.
I want to solve fluid-solid conjugate heat transfer problem which has a cylindrical inner heat sorce and square fluid channel. The model is like this:

Considering that the solid will expand radially and axially when heated, and the expansion of the solid will affect the temperature field and flow field. So I write a thermo-mechanical coupling input file to simulate the effect of elevated temperature on solid deformation. The model of thermo-mechanical coupling input file is like this:

The dimensions of the solid cylinders in both models are identical, and their meshing is identical. Now, I want to incorporate thermo-mechanical coupling into the original fluid-solid conjugate heat transfer. There are many problems that follow, such as the grid displacement of the solid area will also affect the grid of the fluid area. In addition, after the solid is elongated in the axial direction, the fluid cannot wrap the solid. How can I fix this problem? I mean how to solve thermomechanical coupling and fluid-solid conjugate heat transfer simultaneously in one input file.
The first one is fluid-solid conjugate heat transfer input file:
# Units: specific_heat_capacity--cp--J/(kg.K); density--rho--kg/(cm^3);
# dynamic_viscosity--mu--kg/(cm.s); thermal_conductivity--k--W/(cm.K);

g = -981 # cm/s2

[Mesh]

[]

  [../]

For example, the default value of use_displaced_mesh for ADHeatConductionTimeDerivative is true, while that for ADCoupledForce is false. Should I set use_displaced_mesh=true for all objects if I want to simulate thermal coupling as accurately as possible?
